description.text:

Simple to operate, looking good, easy to install, fast removal and installation, easy to print.

I just provided a suggestion of what I liked on my Pan European ST1300 heated grip bike! Added native DesignSpark mechanical (TM) design file.
Please let me know if you improved the original design.

USE ABS
I fixed the ring with a 3mm SST lock metal screw.

The heating of the Felix's heatbed was very slow and it refused to go higher than 88 degrees. I added an isolation sheet made with a piece of cooker hood filter, and attached with 3D-printed clips. Now the bed heats up to 100 degrees without a problem.

Cut out a sheet of cooker hood filter of 25 by 30 cm. Follow the plan in the SVG file for the holes for the mounting screws and cables.  
Unmount the heatbed by unscrewing the 3 nuts at the bottom. Take care not to loose the washers and the springs. Position the isolation sheet and put the 3 screws through the holes. The two ends in the middle at the right side can be fixed together with a piece of tape. Screw the nuts back on and recalibrate the table.  
Print the clip 5 times, and attach 3 of them at the left side, one at the front and one at the back.

title: Bathymetric Laser Cut Map of Arabian Sea

description.text: This is a bathymetric (topography of the sea) chart of the Arabian Sea. The land level includes the markings of the roads for the country Oman as well as the region names and the main cities and some small pictures representing things special to this country. See for yourself in the pictures.

This was my first attempt at making such a chart and once the toolchain is figured out its pretty simple but time intensive. I am planning a larger one but the Lasercutter at my disposal (Fablab AACHEN) is only 300x600mm.
The files use a consistent color scheme for mark, engrave and cut. But this will have to be individually configure in your lasercutter. So to get the data, I went to an LAS Server for bathymetric data
(Live Access to the National Virtual Ocean Data System (NVODS). This was the hardest part to figure out. Live Acess Servers generate renders of datasets such as height information. They are based on a system called Ferret. You can set different parameters on how to render these in 'Plot Options' . I determined the appropriate number of layers to be 12. So the height that I wanted to represent had a resolution of 12. To make it easier to get the vector out of this I rendered it with the following command in the plot options field (-3900,2500,500). This will generate a render that has everything below -3900metres depth white. Once you have this render you need to click print which will open it in a new firefox tab. You want that to happen but you can just click cancel on the print popup. Now you have a picture which can be exported into Illustrator. Then you have to repeat this step while each time rendering the next higher level (-3400,2500,500),(-2900,2500,500)...... then printing it to get the picture output to copy into illustrator. Once you have it in Illustrator you need to posiion these pictures over one another exactly and run an image trace on each with the same settings. It helps to have each picture on a different layer. After that you have to copy and paste (in place) the vector path with the white fill with the 'Select' command . Do this for each 'height'. Voila now you have vectors ready for cutting. I added in some artwork as an engrave but that is completely optional. For the positioning of underwater 'mountains' it helps to mark the positiion of a mountain piece on the next deep layer. I cut out my pieces from plywood panels which were stained with blue color and the top layer with mahogany stain. I hope you have fun with this!

This is a nice simple case for the SmartLCD display with 6-7mm knob post, built-in chirp speaker, and SD card slot on the left side. The SmartLCD comes with many RAMPS kits, including one from Gadgets3D, which is where I got mine as part of their full RAMPS 1.4 kit. Two optional 3mm screws can hold the SmartLCD in place inside the case, or just insert the LCD into the top part first before adding the bottom part. The top and bottom are designed to fit together so no additional hardware is required.

I printed this case in natural PLA and it works really well. I had to file down the tall posts in the back a little to get a fit where the bottom didn't bow, so I may bring the verticals inward a little on the next revision. There are lots of great knobs posted on Thingiverse, or you can use the one that comes with your SmartLCD. I used the one from DeltaPanel by scottmayson. The smartlcd.scad file is from my own measurements. On mine the speaker was mounted on the back. This is an option in the scad file. You can compare my SmartLCD model to the one by sola_technical.

This is based on the plot Z=X*Y (known as a hyperbolic paraboloid or a saddle point) but instead of being a continuous surface, I've discretized it so that it is formed from a collection of varying height square prisms. Aside from looking great, it feels really nice to run your fingers over the discretized surface. Three STL files included:
hyperbolicParaboloid.stl is for a machine with a single extruder. it is formed from 16x16 square prisms, where each square is 3mm per side. hyperbolicParaboloidOddSquares.stl and hyperbolicParaboloidEvenSquares.stl are used for a dual extruder machine so that every other square is a different color (same dimensions as above) Finally I've include the openSCAD source which allows you to parametrize the number of squares per side as well as the size of each square.

This is a proof of concept for a base plate that is mostly cuboid in shape, but should be much less prone to curling up at the corners.  
This is particularly an issue when printing cuboids, which can make printing a model of a building challenging.  
The idea is simple: to reduce the length of any straight sections, where the force exerted by cooling and contracting filament can build up, which is most extreme at the corners and in the first few layers.  
It's a customizable design, so you can create the size of base plate you need to mount your model.  
This is an initial concept I had, there is much more to come around use of texture to prevent warping of models.  
Please share your makes and give attribution, as well as feedback!

The top surface is set at 0 height.  So, if you open it in MakerBot Desktop it will appear below the build surface.  
This is based on the assumption the base of your model will be at 0 height.  
If you centre and level the base plate on your build platform, you need to raise your model up by exactly the height of the build plate you specified, perhaps taking off 0.1mm to ensure the two objects are fully integrated.  
If you specify a base height of 10mm, by the time the print reaches your model, the tendency to curl up should be long gone.

description.text: This is a hanging Nyger (or Niger) bird seed feeder. What is Nyger seed ? http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guizotia_abyssinica Finches love it. Just hang it on a piece of string, fill it with Nyger seed, and the birds will grab onto it with their talons and feast away. The lid keeps the seed dry by shedding water and slides up and down the hanging string so it won't get lost.

Print both pieces.  I made mine yellow because that's the colour of a Nyger flower.  Tie a string (or fishing line, or wire) to the hanging bracket on top.  Thread it through the lid and tie a loop or, if you really want to get fancy, attach a little hoop (maybe 3D print one !)  Then hang it from a tree, or your eaves, or wherever.  The finches love it.  They just grab on with their talons and pig out.  I've seen a half dozen on mine at once swinging around having a feast.

title: Sunhokey Prusa I3 Modification for Smooth Filament Flow

description.text:
So I experienced jumping extruder motor and clogged nozzle and upon investigation I noticed the teeth mark left by the extruder gear on the filament. I suspect this was causing the problem so I tried to adjust the tension on the clamp of the extruder to avoid having teeth mark. But teeth marks still remains and did not solved the problem. Now since I cannot eliminate the teeth mark, I focused on the passage where the filament goes thru. I noticed there are edges that could catch or rub on the teeth mark thus making it hard for the motor to push the filament thru. I have to smooth this edges. So what I did is to put chamfer on this sharp edges. See photos for details. I also put chamfer on the PTFE tube and the one inside the nozzle. Voila!!! problem solved. Oh one more thing, as much as possible, keep your PTFE tube straight up (not leaning forward or backward) to lessen the drag/friction of filament on the tube. Hope this helps everyone having the same problem. Keep printing everyone... cheers! P.S.
Oh just to publish this post I have to put a design file along with this so this is just a dummy file.

description.text:
This is an adapter to attach any smartphone to any eyepiece.
The eyepiece adapter fits on most standard telescope eyepiece diameters, and the smartphone clamp should fit all smartphones (please, put your phablet away, you're embarrassing yourself). It can also be easily adapted to fit the eyepieces of many other scopes. Version 2 modified to use M6 hex head bolts since some hardware stores only stock hex head from M6 upwards, only uses 3 bolts now and has rails to keep it in line. (designed for 0.5mm nozzle). Additional parts required:
3x M6x25 hex head bolt
3x M6 wingnut

Trying to focus a smartphone camera on a telescope eyepiece to catch images of far off galaxies is a hit and miss process that blinds you in the dark.
So I created this simple clamping mechanism that allows you to set the smartphone position and use its screen to constantly view the universe :) As a useful side effect the device can be used for anything that has an eyepiece. (Microscope, Binoculars, Laser welder, etc.)

Print with 0.5 or 0.4mm nozzle. (designed for 0.5, Hex head of bolts may slip if printed with 0.3 nozzle).
I found that you can replace the wingnuts with a strong elastic band around the protruding bolts which pulls the clamps together nicely.
Note: This will not fit an iPhone because as usual the apple products are not compatible with anything not made by apple.

description.text:
A simple plate designed to prevent crushing the mdf of the Oneup or Twoup when securing bearings with zip ties.  I've included the SCAD file so you can play with different thicknesses.  
My OneUP hasn't arrived yet, so this is untested.  May need some tweaking...  
UPDATE: My OneUP arrived today and I got to test these.  They work really well.  The keys fit the slots fine, and the ziptie slots line up like I had hoped.  I use 4mm for the base plate and 1mm for the slot key.  The slot key can be as thick as 3mm (maybe 4) and still work great.  The extra thickness of the slot key will provide even more "crush protection" (even though it's probably not needed.  I think 4mm is just about perfect for the base plate thickness.  It allows the small ziptie blocks to fit perfectly beside it (makes it look neater), and provide plenty of strength.  See instructions for more details.  
Note:  I've added files for the upper extruder bearing and for the gantry (z-travel) bearings.  (Nothing for the lower extruder bearing.)

My OneUP finally arrived and I got to test these.  If you don't have a way to modify the scad file, after testing these, I recommend using either 1upziptieplate4mm.stl or 1upziptiethinkey.stl.  (I used the second one because I already had 6 of them printed ahead of time.  I think I would use the other one otherwise.)  If you can modify the scad file, then I would suggest going with a 4mm plate and 3mm (or maybe even 4mm) key.  
NOTE: There is not a way to use this on the lower extruder assembly.  However, I have added files to use for the upper extruder bearing, and the gantry (z-axis) bearings.  Also included the scad files if you want to modify thickness.  
See scad source file for instructions to modify.  
NOTE:  You will at least need to comment out 3 lines near the beginning of the original file for it to render the first time.  (See comments in file.)
